1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:07,088
When one model call is not enough but the overall path is still controllable, choose the workflow pattern that matches the uncertainty.

2
00:00:07,038 --> 00:00:12,788
The first pattern is prompt chaining: split one difficult task into a sequence of smaller steps.

3
00:00:12,788 --> 00:00:19,365
For example, generate an outline, check it against explicit requirements, and only then draft the document.

4
00:00:19,365 --> 00:00:25,355
Each step solves one clear problem, and a programmatic gate can stop the chain when the output is not ready.

5
00:00:25,355 --> 00:00:28,778
Prompt chaining works when the task decomposes cleanly.

6
00:00:28,778 --> 00:00:33,375
It costs more calls and time, but each call becomes easier to evaluate.

7
00:00:33,375 --> 00:00:41,144
The useful part is the gate: if the outline has no audience, rewrite it; if fact checking fails, do not continue to publication.

8
00:00:41,144 --> 00:00:44,990
Do not let a weak intermediate result travel all the way to the end.

9
00:00:44,990 --> 00:00:47,125
The second pattern is routing.

10
00:00:47,125 --> 00:00:52,038
A router classifies the input and sends it to the right prompt, model, or tool.

11
00:00:52,038 --> 00:00:57,913
Customer requests might branch into product questions, refund requests, and technical incidents.

12
00:00:57,913 --> 00:01:02,778
Common cases can use a smaller model, while unusual cases use a stronger one.

13
00:01:02,778 --> 00:01:08,076
Routing works when categories need clearly different treatment and classification is reliable.

14
00:01:08,076 --> 00:01:10,576
It also needs a low-confidence path.

15
00:01:10,576 --> 00:01:16,307
An uncertain input should go to a general process or a human, not be forced into the wrong branch.

16
00:01:16,307 --> 00:01:20,548
The third pattern is parallelization, and it has two distinct forms.

17
00:01:20,548 --> 00:01:25,288
Sectioning runs independent subtasks at the same time and combines the results.

18
00:01:25,288 --> 00:01:32,355
To evaluate an AI answer, separate reviewers can check facts, safety, clarity, and format in parallel.

19
00:01:32,355 --> 00:01:38,125
Voting asks several independent attempts to judge the same question, then aggregates their conclusions.

20
00:01:38,125 --> 00:01:43,682
A security review might use different prompts to inspect the same code from different risk perspectives.

21
00:01:43,682 --> 00:01:49,355
Parallelization helps when subtasks are independent or when one judgment is not reliable enough.

22
00:01:49,355 --> 00:01:51,221
Independence matters.

23
00:01:51,221 --> 00:01:57,865
Copying the same prompt three times often creates three versions of the same bias, not three useful perspectives.

24
00:01:57,865 --> 00:02:00,596
The fourth pattern is orchestrator-workers.

25
00:02:00,596 --> 00:02:07,932
A central model understands the goal, discovers the required subtasks, delegates them to workers, and combines their results.

26
00:02:07,932 --> 00:02:12,750
The difference from ordinary parallel work is that the subtasks are not known in advance.

27
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:15,798
The orchestrator decides them from the current input.

28
00:02:15,798 --> 00:02:18,336
Consider changing a large codebase.

29
00:02:18,336 --> 00:02:23,548
Before investigation, you do not know how many files must change or which modules matter.

30
00:02:23,548 --> 00:02:28,980
The orchestrator must first inspect the problem, then choose where to search and what work to assign.

31
00:02:28,980 --> 00:02:33,836
This pattern fits complex tasks that can be divided but cannot be fully planned ahead.

32
00:02:33,836 --> 00:02:38,625
Each worker still needs only the relevant context and a consistent return format.

33
00:02:38,625 --> 00:02:43,750
Otherwise, the final synthesis spends most of its budget reinterpreting scattered output.

34
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:46,682
The fifth pattern is evaluator-optimizer.

35
00:02:46,682 --> 00:02:52,932
One model generates a result, another evaluates it, and the first model revises from concrete feedback.

36
00:02:52,932 --> 00:03:00,221
In literary translation, the evaluator can check meaning, tone, and terminology before proposing specific corrections.

37
00:03:00,221 --> 00:03:06,673
The loop works only when feedback can demonstrably improve the result and the evaluator can identify useful changes.

38
00:03:06,673 --> 00:03:13,519
It also needs a stopping condition: reach a score, stop after no improvement, or stop when the budget is exhausted.

39
00:03:13,519 --> 00:03:17,865
Without a clear evaluation standard, the loop only increases cost.

40
00:03:17,865 --> 00:03:20,038
It does not guarantee quality.

41
00:03:20,038 --> 00:03:23,134
The reusable rule is to locate the uncertainty.

42
00:03:23,134 --> 00:03:36,259
Use chaining for fixed steps, routing for different input classes, parallelization for independent work, orchestrator-workers for runtime task discovery, and evaluator-optimizer for outputs that can be explicitly judged and improved.

43
00:03:36,259 --> 00:03:42,451
Patterns can combine, but every addition must solve a named problem, and every step must remain observable.

44
00:03:42,451 --> 00:03:43,990
Chapter recap.

45
00:03:43,990 --> 00:03:47,346
First, locate where uncertainty enters the task.

46
00:03:47,346 --> 00:03:50,980
Second, choose the workflow that controls that uncertainty.

47
00:03:50,980 --> 00:03:54,788
Third, add a pattern only when it solves a specific problem.
